tion]]. The [[Bhusaval Junction railway station|Bhusawal Junction railway station]] was built in 1860, but was not opened for traffic until the mid-1860s. The track was extended to [[Khandwa]] in 1866 and again to [[Nagpur]] in 1867.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-hist.html  | title = IR History: Early Days \u2013 I | last   =Chronology of railways in India, Part 2 (1832 - 1865)| publisher= IFCA| accessdate = 2012-11-20 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url    =http://www.cr.indianrailways.gov.in/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,6,1191,1192,1394,1396,1410,1411 |title = Historical Milestones |publisher= Central Railway| accessdate = 2013-03-24}}</ref>\n\nToday, the Manmad Junction Railway Station is connected to important Indian railway stations including [[Chhatrapati Shivaji Terminus railway station|Mumbai CST,]] [[Pune Junction railway station|Pune Junction]], and [[Secunderabad Junction]].\n\n==Langar Seva==\n{{Main|Langar_(Sikhism)}}\n\nManmad station is the first stop on the [[Sachkhand Express]] route from Sri [[Amritsar]] Sahib to Sachkhand Sri [[Hazur Sahib|Hazur Sahib Nanded]]. [[Sikhs|Sikh]] pilgrims often travel by train on this route. Every day, the local Sikh community from Manmad organizes ''[[Langar (Sikhism)|langar]],'' referring to a free kitchen that serves people of all religions, castes, creeds, and social statuses with free food. It is considered one of the highest forms of humanitarian and community service. Langar can be organized anywhere in India.\n\n== Infrastructure ==\n=== Central Engineering Workshop ===\nThe Central Engineering Workshop located at Manmad has two quarters. The fabrication of [[girder bridge]]s is carried out in the structural yard, while other manufacturing activities are carried out in the general yard and workshop.<ref>{{cite web | URL = http://iricen.indianrailways.gov.in/IRICEN1/projects/812/2.pdf | title = Project: Work fabrication of Steel Girders | publisher = Indian Railways | access-date = 2013-03-26 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160303233935/http://iricen.indianrailways.gov.in/IRICEN1/projects/812/2.pdf | archive-date = 3 March 2016 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Developments ===\nThe developments in this station are very significant. Railways in the Niphad-Manmad-Nandgaon sector were switched to electric power and the locomotives (diesel and electromotive diesel) were changed to electric between 1968 and 1969.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://irfca.org/docs/electrification-history.html|title = History of Electrification|work= |last= |first=| publisher= IRFCA| accessdate = 2013-03-18}}</ref> Manmad has an electric [[locomotive]] trip shed to supply and control the [[train]]s.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-shed.html |title = Sheds and Workshops| publisher= IRFCA| accessdate = 2013-04-02}}</ref> Free high-speed [[Wi-Fi]] has been provided since 2017 for the convenience of passengers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.india.com/business/google-wi-fi-service-available-at-200-stations-across-india-says-indian-railways-full-list-2530613/|title=Google Wi-Fi Service at 200 Railway Stations Across India|last=Desk|first=India com Business|date=2017-10-13|website=India.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-06}}</ref>This establishes Manmad Junction Railway Station among the top 100 most-booked stations within the [[Indian Railways]] system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianrail.gov.in/7days_Avl.html|title=Indian Railways Passenger Reservation Enquiry|work=Availability in trains for Top 100 Booking Stations of Indian Railways|publisher=IRFCA|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140510115649/http://www.indianrail.gov.in/7days_Avl.html|archivedate=10 May 2014|accessdate=2013-03-26}}</ref>These improvements also enhance the well-being and safety of the passengers.\n\nThe Central Railway plans to double the line between [[Daund]] and [[Manmad]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/pune/illegal-settlements-choke-daund-junction-derail-railways-plans-5165101/|title=Illegal settlements choke Daund junction, derail railways\u2019 plans|date=2018-05-06|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2018-06-04|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Location ==\n\n=== Connections ===\n\n==== Airport connectivity ====\nThe distance between Manmad Junction Railway Station (Manmad Jn) and [[Gandhinagar Airport]] is around 88.3&nbsp;km, a trip will last about two hours. Manmad Junction Railway Station (Manmad Jn) and [[Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj International Airport|Chatrapati Shivaji Airport]] (Mumbai Airport) are about 263&nbsp;km apart, and the trip takes about 6 hours and 35 minutes.\n\n====Ankai Fort ====\nThe distance between Manmad Railway Station and [[Ankai Fort]] is {{cvt|10.6|km}}.<ref name=\"erail.in/Information\">{{cite web |title=Manmad Junction Railway Station (MTJ) |url=https://erail.in/info/manmad-railway-station-MMR/24741 |publisher=erail.in}}</ref>\n\n==== Bus connectivity ====\nThe distance between Manmad Junction Railway Station (Manmad Jn) and Manmad Bus Stand, MH SH 10, Bardiya Nagar is 650 m, which takes about 8 minutes to reach.\n\n==== Bus connectivity to Shirdi ====\nThe distance between Manmad Junction Railway Station (Manmad Jn) to Shri SaiBaba Sansthan Trust, Shirdi is {{cvt|57.8|km}} which takes about 1 hour and 38 minutes to travel.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IndiaRailInfo|152}}\n* {{Wikivoyage-inline|Shirdi}}\n* [https://www.cleartrip.com/trains/stations/MMR/ MMR Station]\n\n{{s-rail-start|noclear=yes}}\n{{s-rail|title=Indian Railways}}\n{{s-line|system=[[Chalisgaon Junction railway station]] |previous= Panavedi|next= Summit railway station (India)|line= Central Railway zone|branch= [[Howrah-Nagpur-Mumbai line]], [[Howrah-Allahabad-Mumbai line]], New Delhi-Bhopal-Mumbai line|rows1=1}}\n{{s-line|system= Indian Railways|previous= [[Nandgaon railway station]] |next= Ankai Killa|line= Central Railway zone|branch= Manmad-Daund branch 